  "ExecutionTrace": [
    "Step 0: Idle",
    "Step 1: Thinking\n  [{ Id = b1c41c84-1f52-4ea3-8c83-a4573bb5ef1b\n     CorrelationId = CorrelationId 0e47dd94-857c-4df1-b559-f2b018a38248\n     Sender = System\n     Receiver = Some (Agent (AgentId 5093eb53-d973-4aef-b946-7cd20b7267b7))\n     Performative = Request\n     Intent = Some Coding\n     Constraints = { MaxTokens = None\n                     MaxComplexity = None\n                     Timeout = None\n                     KnowledgeBoundary = [] }\n     Ontology = None\n     Language = \u0022text\u0022\n     Content =\n      \u0022**Task Summary**\n\nThe goal is to write an F# function that calculates the factorial of a number using recursion. The function must handle edge cases for 0 and negative numbers.\n\n**Constraints**\n- Use recursion.\n- Handle edge cases for 0 (factorial of 0 should be 1) and negative numbers (should return an error or special value).\n\n**Validation Criteria**\n- Function returns correct factorial values.\n\n**Solution**\n\nTo achieve this, we will write a recursive function in F#. The function will check if the input number is negative, zero, or positive. For non-negative inputs, it will recursively calculate the factorial.\n\nHere\u0027s the F# code for the factorial function:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060fsharp\nlet rec factorial n =\n    match n with\n    | n when n \u003C 0 -\u003E \u0022Error: Negative input\u0022\n    | 0 -\u003E 1\n    | _ -\u003E n * factorial (n - 1)\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nThis function uses pattern matching to handle different cases:\n- If \u0060n\u0060 is negative, it returns an error message.\n- If \u0060n\u0060 is zero, it returns 1 (since 0! = 1).\n- For positive numbers, it recursively calls itself with \u0060n - 1\u0060 and multiplies the result by \u0060n\u0060.\n\n**Validation**\n\nTo validate this function, we can test it with various inputs:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060fsharp\nprintfn \u0022%s\u0022 (factorial 5)   // Expected output: \u0022120\u0022\nprintfn \u0022%s\u0022 (factorial 0)   // Expected output: \u00221\u0022\nprintfn \u0022%s\u0022 (factorial -3)  // Expected output: \u0022Error: Negative input\u0022\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\n**Final Solution**\n\nThe F# function to calculate the factorial of a number using recursion is:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060fsharp\nlet rec factorial n =\n    match n with\n    | n when n \u003C 0 -\u003E \u0022Error: Negative input\u0022\n    | 0 -\u003E 1\n    | _ -\u003E n * factorial (n - 1)\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nThis function handles edge cases for negative inputs and correctly calculates the factorial for non-negative numbers.\u0022\n     Timestamp = 2025-12-28 9:06:15 AM\n     Metadata = map [] }]",
